    {
      "id": "PopularPost177777",
      "post_content": "As a seasoned Blue Mage, I can tell you that an intelligent and skilled player should rarely have to lose a game. If you let the opponent play their hand, and counter only the major problems, you should be fine. I find that the second and third turn are the most important. What you do with these turns should be pivotal. That being said, I can tell you two things:  \n  \nA) I like this card. It's a nice counterbalance to blue. Let's be honest- us blue mages sometimes get tired of winning all the time. Nice to see wizards lobbing us a challenge :)  \n  \nB) Any self-respecting Blue player should be able to deal with this as easily as any other color. For me, there's [Mana Leak](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Mana Leak) (if I go first) and [Unsummon](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Unsummon) if I didn't. Problem solved, that is, unless they play a [Silence](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Silence) on my next turn. If it happens it happens. Like I said earlier, a blue mage is very powerful- nice to see them hosed, even from a blue players standpoint. Next time someone... [(see all)](javascript:void(0);)",
      "posted_by": "StreamHopper",
